In view of the above observations, we recommended the Management to:
initiate administrative and legal sanctions against the defaulting contractor for incurring unwarranted slippages and for failure to comply with the terms and stipulations of the contract, require the contractor to show cause why the contract should not be terminated despite the extended delay incurred and subsequently enforce the termination order issued by the Management ;
institute the necessary remedies provided under RIRR of RA No. 9184, such as but not limited to, imposition of liquidated damages for the failure of the contractor to satisfactory complete the work within the time specified in the contract; and disqualification and/or blacklisting the contractor;
conduct assessment for the remaining unfinished work and initiate the immediate take-over process for the terminated project in order to facilitate the completion of the project; and
d) intensify monitoring and supervision of project implementation in order to   avoid such recurrence for other municipal projects.

require the members of the Municipal Solid Waste Management Board to exert effort in revising the 10-year SWM plan consistent with the NSWM framework with complete supporting documents and submit the same to the NSWMC for approval;
instruct the MENRO-Designate to coordinate with the rest of barangays that have not yet established their respective MRF and provide them with technical assistance to facilitate the establishment/construction of their own MRF to immediately implement proper disposal of the municipality’s wastes/garbage;
ensure that the MRF in every barangay are established in accordance with the prescribed specifications and ensure proper utilization after their completion; and
undertake necessary steps to ensure the Municipality’s compliance with the provisions of Republic Act No. 9003 for a more comprehensive solid waste management programs necessary for the attainment of total protection of the environment and general welfare of the public/constituents.

We recommended the following and Management agreed to:
Require the Municipal General Services Office to comply with the provisions of Title IV, Section 20 of COA Circular No. 92-386 dated October 20, 1992 on the accountability of non-existent properties and Title V, Rule 21 and 22 of the same circular on the proper disposal of unserviceable properties;

Require the Municipal Accounting Office and General Services Office to reconcile their records in order to determine the actual balances of PPE and to present fairly the balances of the affected PPE accounts at year-end;

Require the Inventory Committee to strictly comply with the provisions of the Manual on the New Government Accounting System, Volume I on the preparation and submission of inventory reports.  Segregate the report on serviceable property from the unserviceable and/or missing properties;

Hold the official/employees responsible for the missing or non-existing properties under their custody or those issued to them;

Drop the unserviceable properties in compliance with the guidelines set forth by COA Circular No. 92-386 and accordingly effect the adjustment in the books.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
Ensure strict adherence to the provisions of COA Circular No. 77-61 for the proper accounting and control of fuel consumption of the government vehicles and other machineries and equipment;
Require the drivers of the motor vehicles to properly accomplish the Daily Trip Tickets and ensure that the same is approved by the authorized officials and signed by the end users/passengers of the motor vehicle, be serially numbered and summarized at the end of the month in a Monthly Report of Fuel Consumption and submitted to COA for audit purposes;

Require the person in charge of preparation of the Fuel and Oil Consumption Reports to properly account the amount/quantity of fuel received and consumed within the period.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
Require the Bids and Awards Committee to strictly comply with the provisions of RA 9184 and DILG Memorandum Circular No. 2014-155 dated December 17, 2014 on the acquisition of motor vehicle;
Require the BAC to justify the conduct of procurement process without the appropriation, non-inclusion in the approved Annual Procurement Plan and absence of Authority to Purchase Motor Vehicle prior to bidding;

Ensure strict adherence of the BAC and its Secretariat in complying with the standards set forth by the Act and its IRR (Section 12.2 of the IRR of RA 9184) to avoid disallowance.

We recommended the following:
Comply strictly with all the requirements in the utilization and liquidation of financial assistance to NGOs/POs in accordance with COA Circular No. 2007 dated October 25, 2007;
Submit the liquidation report of the financial assistance of P2,000,000.00 together with the disbursement vouchers and its supporting documents to establish validity and regularity of its utilization;
Instruct the GAWWA Foundation, Inc. to stop charging expenses out of the financial assistance which are not responsive to the basic services of their foundation otherwise, these expenses will be disallowed in audit; and
Conduct a study relative to the financial activity of the foundation in order to come up with a reasonable amount of financial assistance to be extended to them based on their realistic financial deficiency.
